@peeyushb  The command i used to rerun was : 
$ bin/falcon instance -type process -name process6 -rerun -start 2016-01-12T01:00Z -end 2016-01-12T02:00Z

I was not trying to rerun the entire coordinator but one instance of the coordinator.Let me know if I am missing something.

I just started reviewing the code, not fully done with it. 
Please add "safemode" in the below code in  DefaultAuthorizationProvider.authorizeResource else it will not work for admin users/groups

```
            if ("admin".equals(resource)) {
                if (!("version".equals(action) || "clearuser".equals(action) || "getuser".equals(action))) {
                    authorizeAdminResource(authenticatedUGI, action);
                }
```

@sowmyaramesh  : The above suggestion is inaccurate. The code says "allow non-admin users to access version, clearuser and getuser". So we should not add safemode to this code. 

All admin users are treated as superuser by Falcon. Resume is not allowed in safemode. I will update the doc to make this clear and also add section on safemode behavior when authorization is enabled/disabled. 

The UI support for safemode should follow the section above that describes what operations are enabled/disabled in safemode. No need to add a second section here.

@bvellanki : Where does it say that? If you look at authorizeAdminResource it is what validates if the user has admin privileges. 

In startup.properties

```
# The name of the group of super-users
*.falcon.security.authorization.superusergroup=falcon

# Admin Users, comma separated users
*.falcon.security.authorization.admin.users=falcon,ambari-qa

# Admin Group Membership, comma separated users
*.falcon.security.authorization.admin.groups=falcon,staff
```

All admin users are not super users. 

Also in the code isSuperUser method validates only if user is super user or in super user group. authorizeAdminResource vaildates the admin user.

If admin user is not super user then safemode then current code doesn't validate the user. 

```
            if (isSuperUser(authenticatedUGI)) {
                return;
            }

            if ("admin".equals(resource)) {
                if (!("version".equals(action) || "clearuser".equals(action) || "getuser".equals(action))) {
                    authorizeAdminResource(authenticatedUGI, action);
                }
```

I don't think current code works for admin user. Did you test it for admin user not super user case?

Regarding the doc please remove or update " "UI support for safemode" section to refer the previous section then. Thanks!

@sowmyaramesh Please look at the code again. 
`if (isSuperUser(authenticatedUGI)) {
                return;
            }`

This part would let a super user perform setsafemode action. In DefaultAuthorizationProvider.authorizeAdminResource you have
 `if (adminUsers.contains(authenticatedUser) || isUserInAdminGroups(authenticatedUGI)) {
            return;
        }`

This part allows admin users to perform setsafemode action. Everyone else is denied permission to perform setsafemode action

